        <TR>Splitting [the earth] with spades and laid out on hundreds of pointed wedges:</TR>
        <NOTE>While Łdārayanto$, as an active participle in the masculine nominative, is acceptable
                as an irregular form, the precise interpretation of Łpāda$s a and b remains problematic.
        My translation of this verse is therefore tentative, and the description seems too condensed to be fully
        intelligible. Kengo Harimoto has suggested that \msCc\ and \Ed\ might preserve
        the correct reading, in which case the reference would be to soil 
        piled up by millions of insects (Łkīṭakoṭi$°), rather than to points of
        wedges (Łkīlakoṭi$°). Nevertheless, I now think that the reference could
        be Bhīṣma's dying scene in the \MBH, where the great warrior is lying on a bed of hundreds of arrows: 
        Łsa śete śaratalpastho medinīm aspṛśaṃs tadā$: `Then he lay there on his bed of arrows,
        without touching the ground' (\MBH\ 6.115.8ab). The word Łcita$ is used in a similar context in 
        \MBH\ 12.47.4ab: Łvikīrṇāṃśur ivādityo bhīṣmaḥ śaraśataiś citaḥ$: 
        `Bhīṣma, laid on a hundred arrows, was like the Sun with its scattered rays of light.'
        <sep/>
        If this interpretation of \VSS\ 8.17 is correct, the observance described here may require
        The reference to the Earth in Łpāda$ c may have been inspired by lines such as \MBH\
        one to dig the ground, set up wedges, and lie upon them, in the manner of fakirs.
        6.115.11cd: Łrarāsa pṛthivī caiva bhīṣme śāṃtanave hate$:
        `The Earth cried out when Bhīṣma, the son of Śaṃtanu, was killed.'

         In \BhavP\ 4.121, called `The Description of eighty-five observances' (Łvratapañcāśītivarṇana$),
         we find this on Łmahīvrata$:
                <sep/>
               Łdadyāt triṃśatpalād ūrdhvaṃ mahīṃ kṛtvā tu kāṃcanīm$ |<br/>
               Łkulācalādrisahitāṃ tilavastrasamanvitām$ || 152 || <br/>
               Łtiladroṇopari gatāṃ brāhmaṇāya kuṭuṃbine$ | <br/>
               Łdinaṃ payovratas tiṣṭhed rudraloke mahīyate$ || 153 || <br/>
               Łetan mahīvrataṃ proktaṃ saptakalpānuvartakam$ |.<br/>
                <sep/>
        A tentative translation of this passage would go as follows: `One should donate a golden [model of the] Earth
        weighing more than thirty Łpala$s (approx. one kilogram), depicting the chief mountain-ranges,
        together with [the gift of] sesame seeds and clothes---the sesame seeds [weighing] more than
        a Łdroṇa$ (approx. ten kilograms)---to a householder Brahmin. One should keep the milk-observance 
        [i.e., subsisting on nothing but milk] for one day, and one will enjoy delight in Rudraloka.
        This is called the Earth Observance whose range is seven \ae ons.' (I take the values for weights
        from <citep>OlivelleManu</citep><pnum>997</pnum>.) \MatsP\ 101.52 gives similar instructions, 
        as do the descriptions of the Łdharāvrata$ and the Łśubhadvādaśī$ observances in 
        <citep>KaneHistory</citep><pnum>v. 5, 321 and 429</pnum>.
        The \VSS's Łmahīvrata$ seems different, however, and more in line with 
