        <TR>I shall teach you Setubandha, which sports a current whose water of subtle sound (Łnāda$) 
                                cleanses you of the dirt of your sins.</TR>

<TEXT> jihvākaṇṭhorakūlā svaragaṇapulināvartaghoṣā taraṅgā|</TEXT>
        <APP>\vb <LEM>°kaṇṭhora°</LEM> \conj; °kaṇṭhoru° \mssCaCbCc\msNa\msNb\msNc\Ed\oo
                 <LEM>svara°</LEM> \mssALL\msCa\msCb\msNa\msNb\msNc; sura° \msCc\Ed</APP>
        <NOTE>Metre (10.30--33): Łsragdharā$. Note that °Łkaṇṭhora$° is a conjecture based on the context: this line
                speaks about sounds and the production of sounds. For this,
                Łuraḥ$/Łura$ (`chest') seems better than Łūru$ (`thigh').
              It is not immediately evident why Łpāda$s b and c retain feminine endings.
              I take this as qualifying an implied Łnadī$, partly because the similarly structured 10.33 below
              explicitly mentions Łnadī$, even though this may not align with the fact that 
              Setubandha is the name of the ridge of rocks extending from Rāmeśvara to
              Śrī Laṅkā. The authors may have had only a hazy idea of the true nature of Setubandha,
              or refer here to a different pilgrimage place, possibly in Nepal.
              Some of the compounds here are inverted or split:
              understand Łāvartaghoṣā taraṅgā$ as Łghoṣāvartataraṅgā$, 
              Łkumbhīrāghoṣamīnā$ as Łaghoṣakumbhīramīnā$, and 
              Łbhīmanakrā visargā$ as Łvisargabhīmanakrā$.</NOTE>
        <TR>[It is a river, so to say, whose] banks are the tongue, the throat, and the chest, and
                 its sandbanks are the group of vowels (Łsvara$). It ripples with 
                 whirlpools of voiced consonants (Łghoṣa$).</TR>

<PAGEBREAK/>

<TEXT> kumbhīrāghoṣamīnā daśagaṇamakarā bhīmanakrā visargā</TEXT>
