        <NOTE>The interpretation of this verse is tentative. It seems to 
              refer to the episode when Kṛṣṇa was given flowers of the heavenly wishing tree by Nārada.
              Kṛṣṇa failed to pass any of them to his favourite wife Satyabhāmā (note emendation in 
              Łpāda$ a: an original -Łā$ may have been misread as a visarga). 
              Kṛṣṇa's blunder was remedied by a journey to heaven together, and
              by bringing the wishing tree from the world of gods to Satyabhāmā's garden. 
              Nārada told Satyabhāmā that in order for her to have the tree in 
              all of her births, all she has to do is Łtulāpuruṣadāna$,
              one of the Łmahādāna$s. This involves donating as much gold as the weight of the donor. 
              She gave Nārada as much gold as the weight of her husband, Kṛṣṇa, plus
              the tree. After this, Nārada departed to heaven. 
              See <cite>PuranicEnc</cite> s.v. `Satyabhāmā', and  
                        \PadmaP\ 6.88.15--17:
                        Łsatyabhāmovāca |  
