% buddhi not yet developed in the VSS


<TEXT> nigṛhītā visṛṣtaṃ ca bandhamokṣau tu sādhanam||</TEXT> 20:80
        <APP>\vcd <LEM!>nigṛhītā visṛṣtaṃ ca bandhamokṣau tu sādhanam</LEM> \msCa\msCb\msNa; \om\ \Ed</APP>
        <NOTE>Note the in Łpāda$s cd Łnigṛhītā$ should connect to
              Łmokṣa$ and Łvisṛṣṭa$ to Łbandha$, not in the order
              that the text suggests.</NOTE>
        <TR>When [the senses] are controlled, liberation is produced.
            When they are let go, bondage is produced.</TR>

<TEXT> nigṛhītendriyagrāmaḥ svargamokṣau tu sādhanam|</TEXT>
        <TR>If the senses are under control, it means reaching heaven and liberation.</TR>

<TEXT> visṛṣṭa indriyagrāme duḥkhasaṃsārasādhanam||</TEXT> 20:81
        <APP>\vc <LEM>°sṛṣṭa</LEM> \msNa; °sṛṣṭe \msCa\msCb\Ed</APP>
        <APP>\vd <LEM>duḥkha°</LEM> \msNa; \lac1 × kha° \msCa, duḥkhaṃ \msCb\Ed</APP>
        <TR>When the senses are let loose, suffering and transmigration are the result.</TR>

<TEXT> sakalaṃ niṣkalaṃ caiva mana eva vidur{ }budhāḥ|</TEXT>
        <APP>\vb <LEM>mana eva</LEM> \msCa\msCb\Ed; manar{ }eva \msNa</APP>
        <TR>The wise know that the mind can be form-endowed (Łsakala$) 
            and formless (Łniṣkala$).</TR>

<TEXT> sakalaṃ mana nānātve ekatve mana niṣkalam||</TEXT> 20:82
        <TR>When there is multiplicity (Łnānātva$), the mind is form-endowed (Łsakala$).
            When there is oneness, the mind is formless (Łniṣkala$).</TR>


