        <TR>Since he acquired (? Łarjita$?) the six dignities (Łṣaḍbhaga$), he is a 
            Lord (Łbhagavān$). A Bhikṣu dreads (Łbhī$) transmigration.</TR> 
        <NOTE>The mention of the `six Łbhaga$s' is a reference to a wide-spread
              passage on the etymology of the word Łbhagavān$. The passage appears in 
              the \VISNUP\ thus (6.5.71--76):
                Łaśabdagocarasyāpi tasya vai brahmaṇo dvija$ |
                Łpūjāyāṃ bhagavacchabdaḥ kriyate hy upacārataḥ$ || 6.5.71 
                Łśuddhe mahāvibhūtvākhye pare brahmaṇi śabdite$  |
                Łmaitreya bhagavacchabdaḥsarvakāraṇakāraṇe$  || 6.5.72
                Łsaṃbharteti tathā bhartā bhakārorthadvayānvitaḥ$ |
                Łnetā gamayatā sraṣṭā gakārārthas tathā mune$  || 6.5.73
                Łaiśvaryasya samagrasya vīryasya yaśasaḥ śriyaḥ$ | 
                Łjñānavairāgyayoścaiva ṣaṇṇāṃ bhaga itīraṇā$  || 6.5.74
                Łvasaṃti tatra bhūtāni bhūtātmanyakhilātmani$  |
                Łsa ca bhūteṣvaśeṣeṣu vakārārthastato 'vyayaḥ$  || 6.5.75
                Łevam eṣa mahāñ chabdo maitreya bhagavān iti$ |
                Łparamabrahmabhūtasya vāsudevasya nānyagaḥ$ || 6.5.76
                In Wilson's translation (p.~643):
                `The word Bhagavat is a convenient form to be used in the
                adoration of that supreme being, to whom no term is applicable; and therefore
                Bhagavat expresses that supreme spirit, which is individual, almighty, and the
                cause of causes of all things. The letter ŁBh$ implies the cherisher and supporter
                of the universe. By Łga$ is understood the leader, impeller, or creator. The
                dissyllable ŁBhaga$ indicates the six properties, dominion, might, glory,
                splendour, wisdom, and dispassion. The purport of the letter Łva$ is that
                elemental spirit in which all beings exist, and which exists in all beings.
                And thus this great word Bhagavan is the name of Vāsudeva, who is one with the
                supreme Brahma, and of no one else.'</NOTE>


